ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: That portion of the body that lies between the thorax and the pelvis.

Concepts.definition: The cavity located between the lungs and pelvis. It contains the lower esophagus, stomach, pancreas, intestines, liver, gallbladder and spleen.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A flattened, roughly triangular body resting upon the upper end of each kidney; it is one of the ductless glands furnishing internal secretions (epinephrine and norepinephrine from the medulla and steroid hormones from the cortex).

Concepts.definition: A flattened, roughly triangular body resting upon the upper end of each kidney; it is one of the ductless glands furnishing internal secretions (epinephrine and norepinephrine from the medulla and steroid hormones from the cortex).

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The outer region of the adrenal gland consisting of the zona glomerulosa, the zona fasciculata, and the zona reticularis. The adrenal cortex produces and secretes mineralocorticoids, glucocorticoids, and adrenal androgens.

Concepts.definition: The outer region of the adrenal gland consisting of the zona glomerulosa, the zona fasciculata, and the zona reticularis. The adrenal cortex produces and secretes mineralocorticoids, glucocorticoids, and adrenal androgens.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The inner region of the adrenal gland. The adrenal medulla produces, stores, and secretes epinephrine and norepinephrine.

Concepts.definition: The inner region of the adrenal gland. The adrenal medulla produces, stores, and secretes epinephrine and norepinephrine.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Any of the terminal sacs in the lungs through which gas exchange takes place with the pulmonary capillary blood.

Concepts.definition: Any of the terminal sacs in the lungs through which gas exchange takes place with the pulmonary capillary blood.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A gliding joint between the distal ends of the tibia and fibula and the proximal end of the talus.

Concepts.definition: A gliding joint between the distal ends of the tibia and fibula and the proximal end of the talus.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A rounded band or bundle of nerve fibers that connects the two hemispheres of the brain.

Concepts.definition: A rounded band or bundle of nerve fibers that connects the two hemispheres of the brain.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: (AY-nus) The opening of the rectum to the outside of the body.

Concepts.definition: The lower opening of the digestive tract, lying in the cleft between the buttocks, through which fecal matter is extruded.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The major arterial trunk that carries oxygenated blood from the left ventricle into the ascending aorta behind the heart, the aortic arch, through the thorax as the descending aorta and through the abdomen as the abdominal aorta; it bifurcates into the left and right common iliac arteries.

Concepts.definition: The major arterial trunk that carries oxygenated blood from the left ventricle into the ascending aorta behind the heart, the aortic arch, through the thorax as the descending aorta and through the abdomen as the abdominal aorta; it bifurcates into the left and right common iliac arteries.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A small mass that is located in the inferior surface of the aortic arch. It functions as a peripheral chemoreceptor and is composed of glomus cells.

Concepts.definition: A small mass that is located in the inferior surface of the aortic arch. It functions as a peripheral chemoreceptor and is composed of glomus cells.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Small tissue projection existing as a cecal diverticulum with a questionable history of vestigial versus specialized organ.

Concepts.definition: Small tissue projection existing as a cecal diverticulum with a questionable history of vestigial versus specialized organ.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The portion of the upper extremity between the shoulder and the elbow. For clinical purposes this term is also used to refer to the whole superior limb.

Concepts.definition: The portion of the upper extremity between the shoulder and the elbow. For clinical purposes this term is also used to refer to the whole superior limb.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The vessels carrying blood away from the heart.

Concepts.definition: A blood vessel that carries blood away from the heart.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Aryepiglottis
Arytenoid Fold

The paired upper chambers of the heart. The left atrium receives oxygenated blood from the pulmonary vein and pumps blood into the left ventricle. The right atrium receives venous deoxygenated blood from the entire body via the superior and inferior vena cavae and pumps blood into the right ventricle.

Concepts.definition: The paired upper chambers of the heart. The left atrium receives oxygenated blood from the pulmonary vein and pumps blood into the left ventricle. The right atrium receives venous deoxygenated blood from the entire body via the superior and inferior vena cavae and pumps blood into the right ventricle.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Auditory Canal
The external shell-like structure of ear on the side of the head.

Concepts.definition: The external shell-like structure of ear on the side of the head.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The part of the nervous system of vertebrates that controls involuntary actions of the smooth muscles and heart and glands.

Concepts.definition: The part of the nervous system of vertebrates that controls involuntary actions of the smooth muscles and heart and glands.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Axilla; the hollow under the arm where it is joined to the shoulder.

Concepts.definition: The underside concavity where the arm and the shoulder are joined.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The posterior one third of the tongue behind the terminal sulcus that forms the anterior aspect of the oro-pharynx responsible for swallowing and modification of the voice in speech.

Concepts.definition: The posterior one third of the tongue behind the terminal sulcus that forms the anterior aspect of the oro-pharynx responsible for swallowing and modification of the voice in speech.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The distensible sac-like organ that functions as a reservoir of urine, collecting from the kidneys and eliminating via the urethra.

Concepts.definition: The distensible sac-like organ that functions as a reservoir of urine, collecting from the kidneys and eliminating via the urethra.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A nerve network originating from C5 to T1 that supplies cutaneous and muscular innervation to the arm and hand.

Concepts.definition: A nerve network originating from C5 to T1 that supplies cutaneous and muscular innervation to the arm and hand.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The part of the brain that is connected to the spinal cord.

Concepts.definition: Three sections, the midbrain, pons and medulla oblongata, that are located at the base of the brain. The brain stem regulates the central nervous system, and is vital as a conduit for motor and sensory innervations.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An organ composed of grey and white matter containing billions of neurons that is the center for intelligence and reasoning. It is protected by the bony cranium.

Concepts.definition: An organ composed of grey and white matter containing billions of neurons that is the center for intelligence and reasoning. It is protected by the bony cranium.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Not characterized in any other way._A tubular structure through which the blood circulates in the body. Blood vessels constitute a network composed of arteries, arterioles, capillaries, venules, and veins.

Concepts.definition: Not characterized in any other way.
A tubular structure through which the blood circulates in the body. Blood vessels constitute a network composed of arteries, arterioles, capillaries, venules, and veins.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: One of two hemispheric projections of variable size situated in the subcutaneous layer over the pectoralis major muscle on either side of the chest.

Concepts.definition: One of two hemispheric projections of variable size situated in the subcutaneous layer over the pectoralis major muscle on either side of the chest.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Of, or pertaining to, the bronchus.

Concepts.definition: Of, or pertaining to, the bronchus.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Tubular structure in continuation with the trachea, serving as air passage. It terminates in the lung (terminal bronchiole).

Concepts.definition: Tubular structure in continuation with the trachea, serving as air passage. It terminates in the lung (terminal bronchiole).

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The mucosal membranes located on the inside of the cheek, in the buccal cavity.

Concepts.definition: The mucosal membranes located on the inside of the cheek, in the buccal cavity.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Either of the fleshy mounds in the rear pelvic area of the human body formed by the gluteal muscles.

Concepts.definition: Either of the fleshy mounds in the rear pelvic area of the human body formed by the gluteal muscles.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The posterior aspect of the lower extremity that extends from the knee to the foot.

Concepts.definition: The posterior aspect of the lower extremity that extends from the knee to the foot.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A ridge or ridge-like structure.  In humans it usually refers to the trachea.  The carina of trachea is part of the lowest tracheal cartilage which is placed between the orifices of the two bronchi.

Concepts.definition: A ridge or ridge-like structure.  In humans it usually refers to the trachea.  The carina of trachea is part of the lowest tracheal cartilage which is placed between the orifices of the two bronchi.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Either of the two principal arteries on both sides of the neck that supply blood to the head and neck; each divides into two branches, the internal carotid artery and the external carotid artery.

Concepts.definition: One of two arteries that supply oxygenated blood to the head and neck; the left common carotid branches from the aorta and the right common carotid from the innominate (brachiocephalic artery).

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A cluster of cells that function as chemo-receptors, located at the bifurcation of the carotid artery. Its main purpose is to detect changes in the composition of arterial blood.

Concepts.definition: A cluster of cells that function as chemo-receptors, located at the bifurcation of the carotid artery. Its main purpose is to detect changes in the composition of arterial blood.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A type of connective tissue composed of chondrocytes and an extracellular matrix, composed of collagen, elastin, and ground substance. There are three types of cartilage; namely elastic, hyaline, and fibrocartilage.

Concepts.definition: A type of connective tissue composed of chondrocytes and an extracellular matrix, composed of collagen, elastin, and ground substance. There are three types of cartilage; namely elastic, hyaline, and fibrocartilage.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A blind pouch-like commencement of the colon in the right lower quadrant of the abdomen at the end of the small intestine and the start of the large intestine.

Concepts.definition: A blind pouch-like commencement of the colon in the right lower quadrant of the abdomen at the end of the small intestine and the start of the large intestine.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The portion of the brain located at the base of the skull that is responsible for balance, equilibrium and movement.

Concepts.definition: The portion of the brain located at the base of the skull that is responsible for balance, equilibrium and movement.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The outer layer of the cerebrum composed of neurons and unmyelinated nerve fibers. It is responsible for memory, attention, consciousness and other higher levels of mental function.

Concepts.definition: The outer layer of the cerebrum composed of neurons and unmyelinated nerve fibers. It is responsible for memory, attention, consciousness and other higher levels of mental function.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The part of the brain that controls muscle functions and also controls speech, thought, emotions, reading, writing, and learning. The right hemisphere controls the muscles on the left side of the body, and the left hemisphere controls the muscles on the right side of the body.

Concepts.definition: The part of the brain that controls muscle functions and also controls speech, thought, emotions, reading, writing, and learning. The right hemisphere controls the muscles on the left side of the body, and the left hemisphere controls the muscles on the right side of the body.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Relating to a neck, or cervix, in any sense.

Concepts.definition: Relating to a neck, or cervix, in any sense.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: (SER-viks) The lower, narrow end of the uterus that forms a canal between the uterus and vagina.

Concepts.definition: The lower part of the uterus occupying the region between the isthmus of the uterus and the vagina. It is divided into supravaginal and vaginal portions.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The fleshy part of the face bounded by the eyes, nose, ear, and jaw line.

Concepts.definition: The fleshy part of the face bounded by the eyes, nose, ear, and jaw line.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The anterior side of the thorax from the neck to the abdomen. The shape of the chest is often regarded as potential insight into a disease process, as in the case of barrel chest and respiratory dysfunction.

Concepts.definition: The anterior side of the thorax from the neck to the abdomen. The shape of the chest is often regarded as potential insight into a disease process, as in the case of barrel chest and respiratory dysfunction.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The part of the face below the lower lip and including the protruding part of the lower jaw.

Concepts.definition: The part of the face below the lower lip and including the protruding part of the lower jaw.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Blood vessels forming villous structures in the third, fourth, and lateral ventricles of the brain.

Concepts.definition: Blood vessels forming villous structures in the third, fourth, and lateral ventricles of the brain.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A bone of the upper extremity that articulates with the acromion process of the scapula on one end and the sternum on the other.

Concepts.definition: One of a pair of bones linking the scapula and the sternum. The clavicle is part of the pectoral girdle.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The last portion of the vertebral column just below the sacrum consisting of 3-5 rudimentary vertebrae.

Concepts.definition: A small bone located at the bottom of the spine. The coccyx is a result of 3-5 fused rudimentary vertebrae.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The part of the large intestine measured from the cecum to the rectum consisting of ascending, transverse, descending and sigmoid portions. The purpose of the colon is to remove water from digested food prior to excretion.

Concepts.definition: The part of the large intestine measured from the cecum to the rectum consisting of ascending, transverse, descending and sigmoid portions. The purpose of the colon is to remove water from digested food prior to excretion.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A bundle of nerve fibers crossing from one side to the other side of the brain or spinal cord.

Concepts.definition: A bundle of nerve fibers crossing from one side to the other side of the brain or spinal cord.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A thin, transparent mucous membrane that covers the posterior surface of lids (palpebral conjunctiva) and the outer surface of the sclera (bulbar conjunctiva).

Concepts.definition: A thin, transparent tissue divided into the palpebral conjunctiva (covering the inner side of the eye lid) and the bulbar conjunctiva (covering the eyeball).

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A dome-shaped, transparent, avascular tissue covering the front of the eye. It is composed of five layers: squamous epithelium, Bowman's membrane, stroma, Descemet's membrane, and endothelium. Refraction of light contributing to eye's focusing ability is its characteristic function. It contains unmyelinated nerve endings which are responsible for the high sensitivity of the tissue.

Concepts.definition: A dome-shaped, transparent, avascular tissue covering the front of the eye. It is composed of five layers: squamous epithelium, Bowman's membrane, stroma, Descemet's membrane, and endothelium. Refraction of light contributing to eye's focusing ability is its characteristic function. It contains unmyelinated nerve endings which are responsible for the high sensitivity of the tissue.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Coronoid
A cartilage ring around the trachea below the thyroid cartilage.

Concepts.definition: A cartilage ring around the trachea below the thyroid cartilage.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The muscle that creates the rounded contour of the shoulder which originates from the lateral third of the clavicle, the superior surface of the acromion process, and the posterior border of the spine of the scapula and inserts on the lateral side of the shaft of the humerus. The deltoid muscle is innervated by the brachial plexus arising from the fifth and sixth cervical nerves and controls abduction, extension, flexion, and rotation of the arm.

Concepts.definition: The muscle that creates the rounded contour of the shoulder which originates from the lateral third of the clavicle, the superior surface of the acromion process, and the posterior border of the spine of the scapula and inserts on the lateral side of the shaft of the humerus. The deltoid muscle is innervated by the brachial plexus arising from the fifth and sixth cervical nerves and controls abduction, extension, flexion, and rotation of the arm.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Fibromuscular tissue that separates the thoracic from the abdominal cavity. It increases the volume of the thoracic cavity through contractions, thus facilitating respiration.

Concepts.definition: Fibromuscular tissue that separates the thoracic from the abdominal cavity. It increases the volume of the thoracic cavity through contractions, thus facilitating respiration.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: (doo-ah-DEE-num) The first part of the small intestine.

Concepts.definition: A jointed tube 25-30 cm long that connects the stomach to the jejunum.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Not characterized in any other way._A sense organ needed for the detection of sound and for establishing balance. The outer ear consists of the auricle, the ear canal as well as the tympanic membrane. The middle ear is made up of an air-filled cavity behind the tympanic membrane that contains the ossicles (malleus, incus and stapes). The inner ear is made up of the cochlea needed for hearing and the vestibular apparatus required for balance.

Concepts.definition: Not characterized in any other way.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A type of hinge joint located between the forearm and upper arm.

Concepts.definition: A type of hinge joint located between the forearm and upper arm.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Ductless glands that secrete substances which are released directly into the circulation and which influence metabolism and other body functions.

Concepts.definition: Ductless glands that secrete substances which are released directly into the circulation and which influence metabolism and other body functions.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The mucous membrane comprising the inner layer of the uterine wall; it consists of a simple columnar epithelium and a lamina propria that contains simple tubular uterine glands. The structure, thickness, and state of the endometrium undergo marked change with the menstrual cycle.

Concepts.definition: The mucous membrane comprising the inner layer of the uterine wall; it consists of a simple columnar epithelium and a lamina propria that contains simple tubular uterine glands. The structure, thickness, and state of the endometrium undergo marked change with the menstrual cycle.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A crescent-like structure located in the upper and posterior surfaces of the testis. It consists of the efferent ductules and the duct of the epididymis. It facilitates the maturation of sperm that is produced in the testis.

Concepts.definition: A crescent-like structure located in the upper and posterior surfaces of the testis. It consists of the efferent ductules and the duct of the epididymis. It facilitates the maturation of sperm that is produced in the testis.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A small cartilagenous flap-like valve that closes over the larynx during swallowing to prevent food entering the lungs.

Concepts.definition: A small cartilagenous flap-like valve that closes over the larynx during swallowing to prevent food entering the lungs.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The portion of the digestive canal between the pharynx and stomach. It is about 25 cm long and consists of three parts: the cervical part, from the cricoid cartilage to the thoracic inlet; thoracic part, from thoracic inlet to the diaphragm; and abdominal part, below the diaphragm to the cardiac opening of the stomach.

Concepts.definition: The portion of the digestive canal between the pharynx and stomach. It is about 25 cm long and consists of three parts: the cervical part, from the cricoid cartilage to the thoracic inlet; thoracic part, from thoracic inlet to the diaphragm; and abdominal part, below the diaphragm to the cardiac opening of the stomach.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A sinus of the meatuses of the nasal cavity.

Concepts.definition: A sinus of the meatuses of the nasal cavity.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Happening or arising or located outside or beyond some limits, or especially, some surface.

Concepts.definition: Happening or arising or located outside or beyond some limits, or especially, some surface.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The limb that is composed of the hip, thigh, leg and foot.

Concepts.definition: The limb that is composed of the hip, thigh, leg and foot.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The region of the body that includes the arm, the forearm, and hand.

Concepts.definition: The region of the body that includes the arm, the forearm, and hand.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The organ of sight or vision.

Concepts.definition: The organ of sight or vision.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A thin membrane of skin with the purpose of covering and protecting an eye.

Concepts.definition: A thin membrane of skin with the purpose of covering and protecting an eye.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The anterior portion of the head that includes the skin, muscles, and structures of the forehead, eyes, nose, mouth, cheeks, and jaw. (MeSH)

Concepts.definition: The anterior portion of the head extending from the forehead to the chin and ear to ear. The facial structures contain the eyes, nose and mouth, cheeks and jaws.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: One of a pair of tubes that extend from the uterus to each of the ovaries. Following ovulation the egg travels down the fallopian tube to the uterus where fertilization may or may not occur.

Concepts.definition: One of a pair of tubes that extend from the uterus to each of the ovaries. Following ovulation the egg travels down the fallopian tube to the uterus where fertilization may or may not occur.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The longest and largest bone of the skeleton, it is situated between the hip and the knee.

Concepts.definition: The upper leg bone positioned between the pelvis and the knee.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The bone of the lower leg lateral to and smaller than the tibia. In proportion to its length, it is the most slender of the long bones.

Concepts.definition: The small, lateral calf bone extending from the knee to the ankle.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Any of the digits of the hand.

Concepts.definition: Any of the digits of the hand.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The horseshoe-shaped part of the oral cavity bounded superiorly by the ventral surface of the tongue, inferiorly by the mylohyoid muscle, anterolaterally by the gingival surfaces of the mandible, and posteriorly by the anterior tonsillar pillar.

Concepts.definition: The horseshoe-shaped part of the oral cavity bounded superiorly by the ventral surface of the tongue, inferiorly by the mylohyoid muscle, anterolaterally by the gingival surfaces of the mandible, and posteriorly by the anterior tonsillar pillar.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The structure found below the ankle joint required for locomotion.

Concepts.definition: The structure found below the ankle joint.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The structure on the upper limb, between the elbow and the wrist.

Concepts.definition: The structure on the upper limb, between the elbow and the wrist.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The part of the face between the eyebrows and the normal hairline.

Concepts.definition: The part of the face between the eyebrows and the normal hairline.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The paired, mucosal lined air spaces located above the orbit and communicating with the nasal passages.

Concepts.definition: The paired, mucosal lined air spaces located above the orbit and communicating with the nasal passages.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A pear-shaped organ just below the liver that stores the bile secreted by the liver, delivering the bile through the bile ducts into the intestines to help with digestion.

Concepts.definition: A pear-shaped organ located under the liver that stores and concentrates bile secreted by the liver. From the gallbladder the bile is delivered through the bile ducts into the intestine thereby aiding the digestion of fat-containing foods.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The upper gastrointestinal (GI) tract is comprised of mouth, pharynx, esophagus and stomach while the lower GI tract consists of intestines and anus. The primary function of the GI tract is to ingest, digest, absorb and ultimately excrete food stuff.

Concepts.definition: The upper gastrointestinal (GI) tract is comprised of mouth, pharynx, esophagus and stomach while the lower GI tract consists of intestines and anus. The primary function of the GI tract is to ingest, digest, absorb and ultimately excrete food stuff.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The mucous membrane-covered tissue of the jaws that surrounds the bases of the teeth.

Concepts.definition: The soft tissue surrounding the neck of individual teeth as well as covering the alveolar bone. The tissue is fibrous and continuous with the periodontal ligament and mucosal covering.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Glossopharyngeal
The space in which the vocal cords are located.

Concepts.definition: The space in which the vocal cords are located.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The external junctural region between the lower part of the abdomen and the thigh.

Concepts.definition: The external junctural region between the lower part of the abdomen and the thigh.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The distal portion of the upper extremity. It consists of the carpus, metacarpus, and digits.

Concepts.definition: The distal portion of the upper extremity. It consists of the carpus, metacarpus, and digits.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Not characterized in any other way._The anterior and superior part of a human bearing the mouth, the brain and sensory organs.

The anterior and superior part of a human bearing the mouth, the brain and sensory organs.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Not characterized in any other way._A hollow organ located slightly to the left of the middle portion of the chest. It is composed of muscle and it is divided by a septum into two sides: the right side which receives de-oxygenated blood from the body and the left side which sends newly oxygenated blood to the body. Each side is composed of two chambers: the atrium (receiving blood) and ventricle (ejecting blood).

Concepts.definition: Not characterized in any other way.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A depression or fissure where vessels or nerves or ducts enter a bodily organ.

Concepts.definition: A depression or fissure where vessels or nerves or ducts enter a bodily organ.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The lateral prominence of the pelvis from the waist to the thigh.

Concepts.definition: The lateral prominence of the pelvis from the waist to the thigh.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The upper arm bone between the shoulder and elbow.

Concepts.definition: The upper arm bone between the shoulder and elbow.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The portion of the pharynx between the inferior portion of the oropharynx and the larynx.

Concepts.definition: The lower part of the pharynx that connects to the esophagus.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The final section of the small intestine.

Concepts.definition: The final section of the small intestine.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The broad, dorsal, upper, and widest of the three principal bones composing either half of the pelvis.

Concepts.definition: The broad, dorsal, upper, and widest of the three principal bones composing either half of the pelvis.

Inside or closer to the inside of the body or object.

Concepts.definition: Inside or closer to the inside of the body or object.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The most posterior and ventral bone making up the pelvis.

Concepts.definition: The most posterior and ventral bone making up the pelvis.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The bones of the skull that frame the mouth and serve to open it; the bones that hold the teeth.

Concepts.definition: The bones of the skull that frame the mouth and serve to open it; the bones that hold the teeth.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The portion of the small intestine that extends from the duodenum to the ileum.

Concepts.definition: The portion of the small intestine that extends from the duodenum to the ileum.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Veins in the neck which drain the brain, face, and neck into the brachiocephalic or subclavian veins.

Concepts.definition: Veins in the neck which drain the brain, face, and neck into the brachiocephalic or subclavian veins.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: One of the two bean-shaped organs located on each side of the spine in the retroperitoneum. The right kidney is located below the liver and the left kidney below the diaphragm. The kidneys filter and secret the metabolic products and minerals from the blood, thus maintaining the homeostasis. On the superior pole of each kidney there is an adrenal gland. Each kidney and adrenal gland is surrounded by fat.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A joint connecting the lower part of the femur with the upper part of the tibia. The lower part of the femur and the upper part of the tibia are attached to each other by ligaments. Other structures of the knee joint include the upper part of the fibula, located below and parallel to the tibia, and the patella which moves as the knee bends.

The lower part of the femur and the upper part of the tibia are attached to each other by ligaments. Concepts.definition: The lower part of the pharynx that connects to the esophagus.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: One of a pair of viscera occupying the pulmonary cavities of the thorax, the organs of respiration in which aeration of the blood takes place. Each lung is irregularly conical in shape, presenting a blunt upper extremity (the apex), a concave base following the curve of the diaphragm, an outer convex surface (costal surface), an inner or mediastinal surface (mediastinal surface), a thin and sharp anterior border, and a thick and rounded posterior border.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An organ that is part of the lymphatic system, in which T lymphocytes grow and multiply. The thymus is in the chest behind the breastbone.

Concepts.definition: A bi-lobed organ surrounded by a connective tissue capsule. It is located in the upper anterior portion of the chest, behind the sternum. It is composed predominantly of lymphocytes and fewer epithelial cells. Connective tissue septa separate the lobes into lobules. The lobules contain an outer portion (cortical zone) which is rich in lymphocytes and an inner portion (medullary zone) which is rich in epithelial cells. It is an organ essential for the development of the immune system. Its function is the maturation of the progenitor lymphoid cells to thymocytes and subsequently to mature T-cells. It reaches its greatest weight at puberty and subsequently begins to involute.
